KARA MILLER: Thanks
so much, Steve.

00:14:19.158 --> 00:14:22.340
Thanks to Warren,
and especially Carly

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:26.120
who really helped from the
beginning organize this.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:28.710
And we talked about
in the beginning,

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.290
we wanted to bring
somebody who would

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:33.110
talk about an issue
that's of real interest

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:36.810
right now, that would
be fun here from,

00:14:36.810 --> 00:14:40.126
and Eric was the first
person I thought of.

00:14:40.126 --> 00:14:41.750
It is absolutely
right when Steve said,

00:14:41.750 --> 00:14:42.740
there's a lot of biotech here.

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:45.050
There's a lot of really
interesting people and things

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:45.900
going on.

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:48.390
But Eric is a great
person to talk to.

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:52.310
So be thinking as we're
talking of your questions,

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:53.560
because we want to take those.

00:14:53.560 --> 00:14:56.180
And if you're in the
room, there's the mics.

00:14:56.180 --> 00:14:57.170
There's Dory.

00:14:57.170 --> 00:14:59.430
If you're listening,
there's tweeting.

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:01.470
We're looking at your tweets.

00:15:01.470 --> 00:15:05.800
So feel free to be part
of the conversation.

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:09.340
And as we said, as Steve alluded
to, there's a quiz coming up.

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.110
Literally, there's
a quiz coming up.

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:13.910
But let's just start with this.

00:15:13.910 --> 00:15:17.680
And you've sort of
traveled this path

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:21.660
of learning about learning,
like what learning really means.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:24.520
And I think we're at a point--
I mean, you teach at Harvard--

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:26.500
but we're at this point
of higher education

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:28.990
where, if you go
to private school

00:15:28.990 --> 00:15:34.140
north of $200,000
a year-- I mean

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:36.110
$200,000 for the four years.

00:15:36.110 --> 00:15:38.445
Getting to about a
quarter million dollars

00:15:38.445 --> 00:15:40.430
to go to college.

00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:42.710
And I think people
wonder, is it worth it?

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:44.750
Is it worth a tremendous
amount of paying back

00:15:44.750 --> 00:15:49.260
student loans, a
tremendous amount of debt?

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:53.580
And you've seen how college
average-- what's your view?

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:56.460
ERIC MAZUR: Well, I think if
you look at the data they still

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:58.870
show that it's worth
paying that amount of money

00:15:58.870 --> 00:16:02.240
for future returns.

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:05.180
The real question is, are
we using that money wisely

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:08.390
and educating people
in the optimal way?

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:11.410
And that is not
immediately obvious to me.

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:13.680
KARA MILLER: What are we
doing in those four years

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:18.382
that you see as potentially
not using the money wisely?

00:16:18.382 --> 00:16:20.590
ERIC MAZUR: Well, I think
if you look at the approach

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:24.940
to teaching in most
classroom settings,

00:16:24.940 --> 00:16:30.080
both in higher education and
also in K through 12 education,

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:33.580
it's a very antiquated
approach focusing mainly

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:36.740
on information transfer.

00:16:36.740 --> 00:16:39.020
In fact, when I started
teaching at Harvard,

00:16:39.020 --> 00:16:41.870
which is now, what,
over 30 years ago?

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:46.410
I never asked
myself the question,

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:47.970
how am I going to teach?

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:50.350
It was patently obvious
what I was going to do.

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:52.960
I was going to do
my students what

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:54.950
my professors had done to me.

00:16:54.950 --> 00:16:59.290
And it's not because I wanted
to take revenge or anything.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:02.120
It's basically because
I naively believed,

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:05.180
I learned it in a room not
very different from this one,

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:09.290
with everybody facing me and
the professors talking to me.

00:17:09.290 --> 00:17:11.540
So that's how one learns.

00:17:13.369 --> 00:17:15.660
So in a sense, I projected
my own experiences

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:19.569
and didn't really ask
myself, where did I learn it?

00:17:22.360 --> 00:17:24.609
KARA MILLER: You were doing
the classic lecture, which

00:17:24.609 --> 00:17:28.109
we've all been in
many, many times.

00:17:28.109 --> 00:17:30.980
Were the students that
were learning from you

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:34.720
absorbing the material that
you were giving to them?

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:36.036
How much were they learning?

00:17:36.036 --> 00:17:38.160
ERIC MAZUR: I don't know
if they were absorbing it.

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:40.660
Somebody once described
the lecture as a process

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.820
whereby the lecture
notes of the instructor

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:46.890
get transferred to the
notebooks of the students

00:17:46.890 --> 00:17:50.320
without passing through
the brains of either.

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:52.820
That's pretty much what was
going on in my classroom.

00:17:52.820 --> 00:17:54.570
Let me give you a
little bit more context.

00:17:54.570 --> 00:17:57.590
I was asked to teach the class
that none of my colleagues

00:17:57.590 --> 00:18:02.034
wanted to teach, physics
for pre-medical students.

00:18:02.034 --> 00:18:04.200
These were not students who
wanted to learn physics.

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:06.810
They already dreaded
physics before setting foot

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:09.260
into my classroom.

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:12.880
At the end of the semester, the
evaluations of the instructor,

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:14.876
these pre-meds tended
to be very harsh.

00:18:14.876 --> 00:18:16.250
This is why none
of my colleagues

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:19.070
wanted to teach that course.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:22.050
And I, as an assistant
professor who

00:18:22.050 --> 00:18:23.980
had not been educated
in this country,

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:25.020
didn't know any of this.

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:26.960
So I just accepted
this assignment.

00:18:26.960 --> 00:18:29.480
Not that I had choice.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:33.890
And what happened was
actually quite interesting.

00:18:33.890 --> 00:18:36.420
The idea that I was
doing the right thing

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:41.260
got reinforced, because
the students ended up

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:42.380
high valuations.

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:45.410
Four point five on
a five-point scale.

00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:48.630
They did well on the
examinations I gave them.

00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:51.500
So I pretty quickly
became convinced

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:53.730
that I was the world's
best physics teacher.

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:57.420
KARA MILLER: And then?

00:18:57.420 --> 00:18:58.830
ERIC MAZUR: And then.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:01.330
KARA MILLER: I'm guessing
this doesn't end here,

00:19:01.330 --> 00:19:03.550
in sweetness and
light and rainbows.

00:19:03.550 --> 00:19:07.770
ERIC MAZUR: Well, it went
on for quite a few years.

00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:09.530
I think seven or so.

00:19:09.530 --> 00:19:14.192
And then in my seventh year,
just for getting tenure

00:19:14.192 --> 00:19:19.000
at Harvard, I came across
an article that showed data,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
basically that made an
instrument, a questionnaire,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.920
if you want, using
word-based questions.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:26.590
So no drawings, no equations.

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:29.360
Just words, to test
students' understanding

00:19:29.360 --> 00:19:31.187
of very basic physics.

00:19:31.187 --> 00:19:33.020
Essentially, the concept
of force, which you

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:38.510
learn in week one in
my course at Harvard.

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:42.040
And it showed that, in the
southwest of the US-- Arizona,

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:47.280
New Mexico, California--
if you test students

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:49.730
at the beginning of the term
and then you try it again

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:53.940
after two semesters,
there's no difference

00:19:53.940 --> 00:19:55.720
between the pretest
at the beginning

00:19:55.720 --> 00:19:56.930
and the post-test at the end.

00:19:56.930 --> 00:19:59.290
And in both cases,
quite a few students

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:01.250
score even below
what a gorilla would

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:02.970
score by just
pressing random keys.

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:08.080
I thought, no way.

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:09.607
No way.

00:20:09.607 --> 00:20:11.940
But I'm a scientist, so one
of things I've learned to do

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:14.800
is not just to make a statement.

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:19.020
I thought, I'm going to show
that my students at Harvard

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:19.874
do much better.

00:20:19.874 --> 00:20:21.540
This was all in the
southwest of the US,

00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:24.520
so I thought, maybe there's
some disease raging there.

00:20:24.520 --> 00:20:28.450
Up here in the Northeast I'm
sure things are much better.

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:30.560
So it was too late
to do a pretest.

00:20:30.560 --> 00:20:33.790
We were already two-thirds
into the semester.

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:36.040
So I gave it to my students.

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:41.290
It took no more than
one minute to tumble out

00:20:41.290 --> 00:20:43.860
of my ivory tower,
because as soon

00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:46.930
as they started looking
at the questions

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:50.470
on this questionnaire, one
student raise their hand.

00:20:50.470 --> 00:20:52.890
I walked over to her
and she asked me,

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:57.540
Professor Mazur, how should
I answer these questions?

00:20:57.540 --> 00:21:01.060
According to what you taught
us or according to the way

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:04.840
I usually think
about these things?

00:21:04.840 --> 00:21:07.290
I had no idea how to answer
that question, and by the time

00:21:07.290 --> 00:21:10.190
the test had been completed
I had been dragged out

00:21:10.190 --> 00:21:11.810
of my ivory tower.

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:15.400
KARA MILLER: So now,
that seems to say

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:18.540
since an awful lot of
information transfer

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:23.140
goes on by professor is
lecturing to their students,

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:25.740
and if those students
aren't absorbing anything,

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:29.310
then what do we make of
what goes on in colleges?

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:31.450
I come back to you.

00:21:31.450 --> 00:21:33.270
That's worth a quarter
million dollars?

00:21:33.270 --> 00:21:36.450
ERIC MAZUR: Well clearly, I
think we still generate people

00:21:36.450 --> 00:21:38.900
that end up doing better
than the people who

00:21:38.900 --> 00:21:40.180
don't go to college.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:40.940
KARA MILLER: But is
that just because they

00:21:40.940 --> 00:21:42.230
have a piece of paper?

00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:44.514
ERIC MAZUR: Well, I
like to say that you

00:21:44.514 --> 00:21:45.930
take the types of
students that we

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:47.770
get in an institution
like mine-- Harvard,

00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:50.777
or any other comparable
institution--

00:21:50.777 --> 00:21:53.360
even if you were to put them in
a closet for four years they'd

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:54.450
come out smarter, right?

00:21:54.450 --> 00:21:56.380
Because they're a
select group of students

00:21:56.380 --> 00:21:58.120
that takes ownership
of their learning.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:00.630
So you almost can't go wrong.

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:06.830
But I think what that little
anecdote that I just told you

00:22:06.830 --> 00:22:10.640
about, which is true anecdote,
with that made me realize

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:13.530
is that, in the
classroom I had been

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:16.340
focusing on
information transfer.

00:22:16.340 --> 00:22:19.580
I had basically been
transferring information

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:25.950
to the students as if the book
had not even been invented yet.

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:30.704
In a sense I was
transferring the information

00:22:30.704 --> 00:22:32.120
from the textbook
to the students.

00:22:34.705 --> 00:22:37.330
And education is, of course, so
much more, because as a learner

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:39.121
you need to make sense
of that information.

00:22:39.121 --> 00:22:40.900
It's not enough
just to put it down

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:45.715
in your notes in your notebook
or try to remember it.

00:22:45.715 --> 00:22:47.673
You have to do something
with that information.

00:22:47.673 --> 00:22:50.700
You have to extract whatever
understanding, mental models,

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:54.090
interpretations there are that
you can apply in a new context.

00:22:54.090 --> 00:22:55.170
Right?

00:22:55.170 --> 00:22:57.680
Because we don't want to
train our students to only

00:22:57.680 --> 00:22:59.992
be able to solve the
problems that we teach them

00:22:59.992 --> 00:23:00.700
in the classroom.

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:04.920
Later on they'll take on
jobs that we don't even

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:06.364
have words for.

00:23:06.364 --> 00:23:09.862
20 years ago the word "Google"
wouldn't have meant anything.

00:23:09.862 --> 00:23:11.570
If somebody would have
come to me saying,

00:23:11.570 --> 00:23:13.670
I need a web
programmer, I would have

00:23:13.670 --> 00:23:16.880
had no idea what the
person was talking about.

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:19.406
So we need to prepare
students for the unknown.

00:23:19.406 --> 00:23:21.280
And therefore, it's not
just the information.

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:24.640
It's sort of the mental models,
the skills, that underlie,

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:28.520
that transcendent, in a certain
sense, that information.

00:23:28.520 --> 00:23:30.740
So I see education as
a two-step process.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:33.520
One, information transfer.

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:36.980
Two, making sense
of that information.

00:23:39.550 --> 00:23:42.180
And I ask myself
next, where did I

00:23:42.180 --> 00:23:43.860
make sense of that information?

00:23:43.860 --> 00:23:49.730
Where did I have the aha
moments, the, oh, I get it now.

00:23:49.730 --> 00:23:50.920
Ask yourself that question.

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:53.310
I mean, you've been
in college classes.

00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:54.780
You've sat there, right?

00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:58.400
How many times did you go
"aha" in the classroom?

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:00.840
I think usually you go "aha"
outside of the classroom when

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:02.580
you struggle with
all the information

00:24:02.580 --> 00:24:03.790
that you've taken down.

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:06.840
In part, that's because when
you're listening to somebody

00:24:06.840 --> 00:24:10.310
speak, when you're
listening to a lecture,

00:24:10.310 --> 00:24:12.100
there's no time to think.

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:12.920
Right?

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:15.330
I mean, if you think,
your mind wanders

00:24:15.330 --> 00:24:17.110
and you're no longer listening.

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:19.442
Our brains are just not
wired for multitasking.

00:24:19.442 --> 00:24:21.400
KARA MILLER: Joy Ito,
who some of you may know,

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:26.800
who runs the MIT
Media Lab-- he worked

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:28.915
with a lot of roboticists--
had somebody attach

00:24:28.915 --> 00:24:33.040
a sensor to a student as
