00:24:42.972 --> 00:24:45.180
There's a certain amount
that goes on when you sleep,

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:47.670
but in class they
were really resting.

00:24:51.280 --> 00:24:52.510
OK, so you learn this.

00:24:52.510 --> 00:24:54.010
You learn that
the physics is not

00:24:54.010 --> 00:24:57.230
being transferred, that people
don't really understand force.

00:24:57.230 --> 00:24:58.080
What do you do?

00:24:58.080 --> 00:25:01.102
How do you reshape your
classroom after that right?

00:25:01.102 --> 00:25:02.560
ERIC MAZUR: So if
you see education

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:05.240
as a two-step process,
information transfer making

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:08.860
sense, and you
realize that educators

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:10.890
put most of their effort
on the first step,

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:13.225
leaving the second step to
the students on their own,

00:25:13.225 --> 00:25:15.350
if you think about it
pragmatically it doesn't make

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:17.308
much more sense to have
students be responsible

00:25:17.308 --> 00:25:19.270
for the information transfer.

00:25:19.270 --> 00:25:24.020
And you, as the teacher
there, in order to help them

00:25:24.020 --> 00:25:25.280
make sense of the information.

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:28.260
So basically, it boils down
to inverting this approach.

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:30.210
Flipping it, as it's called now.

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:34.220
So push the information transfer
outside of the classroom

00:25:34.220 --> 00:25:38.040
so that you don't have to
regurgitate a textbook to them.

00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:40.000
You can do that with
video or a book.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.140
And then in class,
do something that

00:25:42.140 --> 00:25:44.770
helps them build understanding.

00:25:44.770 --> 00:25:46.250
