KARA MILLER: Fantastic.

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:06.160
ERIC MAZUR: So
thermal expansion is

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:09.764
something that is really
important in engineering.

00:30:09.764 --> 00:30:11.305
Thermal expansion
deals with the fact

00:30:11.305 --> 00:30:17.350
that hard solids, like wood
or steel or stone or concrete,

00:30:17.350 --> 00:30:23.450
expand when they get hotter and
contract when they get colder.

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:25.770
For example, you may have
been in a train at low speed

00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:28.330
and heard this clickety-clack
sound of the wheels

00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:31.079
as the wheels go over gaps in
different sections of the rail.

00:30:31.079 --> 00:30:32.620
You may have wondered,
why don't they

00:30:32.620 --> 00:30:34.740
just jam the rails together?

00:30:34.740 --> 00:30:38.340
Well, if they were not
leaving that little gap

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:40.700
between different sections
of the rail and the weather

00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:43.600
heats up and the rail
expands, bad things

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:46.220
happen, as you can
see on the screen.

00:30:46.220 --> 00:30:48.440
Same thing with steel-beam
buildings, like this one.

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:49.990
You need to take into
account the expansion

00:30:49.990 --> 00:30:51.290
of the steel in hotter weather.

00:30:51.290 --> 00:30:54.720
Otherwise, things can go
wrong with the expansion.

00:30:54.720 --> 00:31:00.270
Next time you park your car in a
big concrete parking structure,

00:31:00.270 --> 00:31:04.430
look down and you'll see that
the concrete doesn't extend

00:31:04.430 --> 00:31:07.650
all the way from one side to
the other, but there are gaps.

00:31:07.650 --> 00:31:11.650
Every 30 yards or so, there's
a gap filled with rubber

00:31:11.650 --> 00:31:15.010
to permit the
concrete to expand.

00:31:15.010 --> 00:31:19.570
Now, you may wonder
why materials expand.

00:31:19.570 --> 00:31:21.240
Well, materials--
solids, I should

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:23.370
say-- are made, like
any other material,

00:31:23.370 --> 00:31:26.470
from atoms that are
usually in fixed positions.

00:31:26.470 --> 00:31:31.340
And atoms get further away from
each other when it gets hotter.

00:31:31.340 --> 00:31:35.080
So this is cold, and that's hot.

00:31:35.080 --> 00:31:37.420
Cold, and hot.

00:31:39.777 --> 00:31:40.860
That's all there is to it.

00:31:40.860 --> 00:31:44.730
That's the only thing
I'm going to test you on.

00:31:44.730 --> 00:31:46.480
I won't test you on
it, but you my wonder,

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:48.940
why is it that they get
further away from each other?

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:52.440
The reason is that atoms
don't sit still, they vibrate.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:53.900
And the amplitude
of that vibration

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:55.600
is what we call temperature.

00:31:55.600 --> 00:31:57.610
So when you touch
something, in a sense

00:31:57.610 --> 00:32:00.570
you feel the energy
associated with the atoms that

00:32:00.570 --> 00:32:02.340
are moving back and forth.

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:04.284
If you are cold you
have little amplitude.

00:32:04.284 --> 00:32:05.950
If you're hot, you
have a big amplitude,

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:08.440
which means you need more space.

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:12.610
And they all push
each other away.

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:14.410
Not just the nine that
are on the screen.

00:32:14.410 --> 00:32:15.090
All of them.

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:17.975
The millions, billions of
atoms that make up a solid.

00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:24.047
Cold, and hot.

