00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:22.520
Why don't you all
press a button?

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:24.800
And then you'll see that
this number here-- I

00:35:24.800 --> 00:35:27.500
can zoom in-- so you
can see it goes up.

00:35:27.500 --> 00:35:28.180
OK, very good.

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:30.435
The people who are remote,
there'll be a slight delay

00:35:30.435 --> 00:35:31.670
but it'll go up.

00:35:31.670 --> 00:35:35.410
And at any point, I can
display the distribution.

00:35:35.410 --> 00:35:38.780
Why don't you all press one?

00:35:38.780 --> 00:35:41.890
I love it when audiences
follow my instruction.

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:43.130
Thank you.

00:35:43.130 --> 00:35:47.880
OK, and then when I hit stop
here you can no longer vote.

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:50.630
So this is what
we're going to do.

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:53.632
I'm going you ask
you a question.

00:35:53.632 --> 00:35:56.090
You're going to think about
the question, about the answer.

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:58.450
It's going to be
multiple choice.

00:35:58.450 --> 00:36:00.000
You press a button
that corresponds

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:01.790
to the answer you
think is correct.

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:05.590
If you change your mind
before I close the polling,

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:07.230
you can change your mind.

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:10.280
You can press, let's say,
first five and then seven.

00:36:10.280 --> 00:36:12.270
The seven will
override the five.

00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:14.920
Once I stop it you can
no longer change it.

00:36:14.920 --> 00:36:16.715
I don't want you to
talk to anybody else.

00:36:16.715 --> 00:36:20.820
I want your individual
commitment on that first round.

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:22.320
If I hear you talk
to somebody else,

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:24.210
I'll come to you
with this microphone

00:36:24.210 --> 00:36:26.220
and you'll have to tell
everybody what you just

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:28.820
told him.

00:36:28.820 --> 00:36:30.790
Then, I'm going
to ask you to find

00:36:30.790 --> 00:36:32.564
a neighbor who has
a different answer.

00:36:32.564 --> 00:36:34.980
So you turn to your neighbor
and you're right and you say,

00:36:34.980 --> 00:36:36.110
I chose this answer.

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:38.580
If that neighbor
has the same answer,

00:36:38.580 --> 00:36:40.160
you say, thank you
very much, and you

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:41.510
turn to the person on your left.

00:36:41.510 --> 00:36:43.343
If everybody around you
has the same answer,

00:36:43.343 --> 00:36:44.480
get up and walk around.

00:36:44.480 --> 00:36:47.015
You have to find somebody
who has a different answer.

00:36:47.015 --> 00:36:49.630
If you just sit there
without talking to anybody,

00:36:49.630 --> 00:36:52.660
I will come and talk to you.

00:36:52.660 --> 00:36:54.770
So find somebody
else and then try

00:36:54.770 --> 00:36:56.520
to convince that person
that you are right

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:57.950
and he or she is wrong.

00:36:57.950 --> 00:36:59.290
OK?

00:36:59.290 --> 00:37:00.330
Clear?

00:37:00.330 --> 00:37:01.900
Good.

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:03.150
So here is the question.

00:37:06.900 --> 00:37:09.110
Consider a rectangular
metal plate

00:37:09.110 --> 00:37:12.290
with a circular hole in it.

00:37:12.290 --> 00:37:15.620
When the plate is
uniformly heated,

00:37:15.620 --> 00:37:18.890
what happens to the
diameter of-- I haven't even

00:37:18.890 --> 00:37:21.330
read the question and there's
already three people who

00:37:21.330 --> 00:37:24.180
have answered-- what happens
to the diameter of the hole?

00:37:24.180 --> 00:37:25.880
Does it increase?

00:37:25.880 --> 00:37:28.030
Does it stay the same?

00:37:28.030 --> 00:37:30.645
Or does it decrease?

00:37:30.645 --> 00:37:32.770
I'm going to give you one
minute to think about it.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.850
OK, so if you don't have the
answer right now, don't worry.

00:38:06.850 --> 00:38:07.960
Nothing depends on it.

00:38:07.960 --> 00:38:09.810
Your salary will
not be affected.

00:38:09.810 --> 00:38:11.112
Nothing.

00:38:11.112 --> 00:38:12.690
But just make it a game.

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:15.270
I do want you to make a choice.

00:38:15.270 --> 00:38:20.610
So choose whichever you think is
the most reasonable answer, OK?

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:23.600
So we have a reasonable
number of responses,

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:25.200
so now please turn
to your neighbor.

00:38:25.200 --> 00:38:27.480
Find a neighbor who
has a different answer,

00:38:27.480 --> 00:38:29.500
and try to convince that
person of your answer.

00:38:32.390 --> 00:38:35.329
And again, if you don't talk,
I'll come and talk to you.

00:38:35.329 --> 00:40:43.270
[AUDIENCE CHATTER]

00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:46.400
ERIC MAZUR: Now look at this.

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:48.850
You all got engaged.

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:51.960
You got all fired up.

00:40:51.960 --> 00:40:52.590
It's OK.

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:53.140
It's OK.

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:54.125
It's all right.

00:40:54.125 --> 00:40:55.000
You're still talking.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.850
They are gesticulating
about holes and so on.

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:01.630
Hello?

00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:03.210
Hello?

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:05.591
It's OK.

00:41:05.591 --> 00:41:07.090
You probably have
all forgotten here

00:41:07.090 --> 00:41:10.250
that Karen and I are
here not to teach you

00:41:10.250 --> 00:41:12.500
about thermal expansion.

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:14.410
We're here to talk
about education.

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:16.560
The answer to this question
doesn't even matter.

00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:21.190
You've already made my
point, how engaged you got.

00:41:21.190 --> 00:41:25.260
Imagine I had just given my
little lecture, as I did,

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:28.590
and then instead of asking
you this question I said,

00:41:28.590 --> 00:41:31.220
let's now apply this to
rectangular metal plates

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:32.750
with circular holes in it.

00:41:32.750 --> 00:41:35.870
If you take one of these
plates and put it in an oven

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:40.070
and turn up the oven,
the plate expands

00:41:40.070 --> 00:41:43.130
and the diameter
of the hole will--

00:41:43.130 --> 00:41:46.750
I'm going to keep you in
suspense a little bit longer.

00:41:46.750 --> 00:41:48.731
You would have not
been engaged like this.

00:41:48.731 --> 00:41:50.480
You would have been
sleeping through this.

00:41:50.480 --> 00:41:53.590
I mean, what is more boring
than rectangular metal plates

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:56.400
with circular hols in it?

00:41:56.400 --> 00:41:58.140
Isn't it amazing
how you can turn

00:41:58.140 --> 00:42:01.020
on the curiosity
of the human mind?

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.030
Right?

00:42:02.030 --> 00:42:08.460
We're all born curious and
inquisitive, and asking

00:42:08.460 --> 00:42:11.100
for why and reasons
and everything.

00:42:11.100 --> 00:42:12.750
If anything,
education does really

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:15.610
a good job turning that
curiosity off, right?

00:42:15.610 --> 00:42:18.441
It's only later in life
that we rediscover it.

00:42:18.441 --> 00:42:19.940
In a sense, what
I've shown you here

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:23.830
is how easy it is to
reignite that curiosity,

00:42:23.830 --> 00:42:28.550
a curiosity that gives you
ownership of you're learning.

00:42:28.550 --> 00:42:30.040
Now, I know you want the answer.

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:33.110
But before I tell you
what the answer is,

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:34.810
let's analyze what happened.

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:39.500
I asked you a question, and then
I had you make a commitment.

00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:43.460
You had to choose an
answer and press a button.

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:45.011
And after you made
that commitment

00:42:45.011 --> 00:42:46.510
I asked you to turn
to your neighbor

00:42:46.510 --> 00:42:48.590
and to externalize your answer.

00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:51.592
I chose.

00:42:51.592 --> 00:42:53.300
And something interesting
happened there,

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:57.439
because in that explanation--
even though I didn't come down

00:42:57.439 --> 00:42:58.855
from the podium
and listen to you,

00:42:58.855 --> 00:43:00.750
I could see it from
your gesticulation--

00:43:00.750 --> 00:43:03.494
you moved away from the
answer to the reasoning.

00:43:03.494 --> 00:43:04.910
It was no longer
about the answer,

00:43:04.910 --> 00:43:08.430
it was about how you
get to the answer.

00:43:08.430 --> 00:43:11.350
So much education is focused
on the outcome and the answer,

00:43:11.350 --> 00:43:13.430
and students are
evaluated on the answers.

00:43:13.430 --> 00:43:16.490
But in any real world
problem, the outcome is known.

00:43:16.490 --> 00:43:19.480
It's the path to the
outcome that's unknown.

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:20.630
It's a thinking skill.

00:43:20.630 --> 00:43:24.590
This brings the thinking
back in the classroom.

00:43:24.590 --> 00:43:28.350
But most importantly, you
became emotionally invested

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:29.980
in the learning process.

00:43:29.980 --> 00:43:32.590
If Kara were to shut
me down and say,

00:43:32.590 --> 00:43:35.021
Eric, we have only a few
minutes left for questions,

00:43:35.021 --> 00:43:36.520
and then we left,
you'd come running

00:43:36.520 --> 00:43:38.949
after me asking
what the answer is.

00:43:38.949 --> 00:43:41.240
You want to know the answer,
even though we're not here

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:42.573
to talk about thermal expansion.

00:43:42.573 --> 00:43:45.650
We're here to talk
about pedagogy.

00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:49.140
OK, so before I can
give you the answer--

00:43:49.140 --> 00:43:50.740
KARA MILLER: I have
to say, when you

00:43:50.740 --> 00:43:54.160
said, OK, stop talking,
let's talk about why

00:43:54.160 --> 00:43:57.310
you got all fired up, somebody
out there screamed at you,

00:43:57.310 --> 00:43:59.900
what's the answer?

00:43:59.900 --> 00:44:00.987
So talk about fired up.

00:44:00.987 --> 00:44:02.820
ERIC MAZUR: Before I
can tell you the answer

00:44:02.820 --> 00:44:04.310
you need to vote a second time.

00:44:04.310 --> 00:44:06.230
We need a first vote
and a second vote.

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:09.110
So please, vote again,
indicating what you now

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:11.160
believe to be the
correct answer.

00:44:11.160 --> 00:44:13.650
If you've chosen
a certain answer

00:44:13.650 --> 00:44:15.100
and you've not
changed your mind,

00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:16.810
then you just vote
the same thing again.

00:44:16.810 --> 00:44:20.350
But you have to
vote a second time.

00:44:20.350 --> 00:44:23.780
And I'm going to give
you 10 more seconds here.

00:44:23.780 --> 00:44:26.326
And there's a slight delay for
people online, but that's OK.

00:44:31.112 --> 00:44:33.820
I have bad news for you.

00:44:33.820 --> 00:44:37.480
I thought I gave a pretty clear
lecture on thermal expansion,

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:40.512
and so did you.

00:44:40.512 --> 00:44:45.050
You had only 33% got
the right answer,

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:47.174
which means one in three.

00:44:47.174 --> 00:44:48.840
You should really
have done your reading

00:44:48.840 --> 00:44:49.964
before coming to this show.

00:44:52.710 --> 00:44:56.210
Anyway, in a sense
you've helped me

00:44:56.210 --> 00:45:03.510
make a really important point,
because you've been telling me,

00:45:03.510 --> 00:45:07.780
Eric, you're lecturing sucks.

00:45:07.780 --> 00:45:09.260
After all, you got
only 33% right.

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:11.009
But the method doesn't
work that well when

00:45:11.009 --> 00:45:13.280
there's only 33% right,
because it means only one

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:15.120
person of every three people.

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:18.450
Typically you want to
have a higher percentage.

00:45:18.450 --> 00:45:22.180
Anyway, the right
answer is-- oh,

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:26.250
look at all the attention
I'm getting here.

00:45:26.250 --> 00:45:29.650
There's not a single person
looking at his or her computer

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:33.630
screen or texting or tweeting.

00:45:33.630 --> 00:45:35.980
All right, so the right
answer-- I need a new drum

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:41.340
roll-- the right
answer is, number one.

00:45:41.340 --> 00:45:45.160
Let's see what the
second vote was.

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:48.360
A small miracle happened,
because look at this.

00:45:48.360 --> 00:45:52.920
This was the initial
distribution here, 33%.

00:45:52.920 --> 00:45:56.650
So the correct answer
went up, that one-third

00:45:56.650 --> 00:45:58.810
had had the right answer
effectively convinced

00:45:58.810 --> 00:45:59.520
the other.

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:01.450
But there were just
not enough of it.

00:46:01.450 --> 00:46:04.376
So typically want to
choose your questions--

00:46:04.376 --> 00:46:05.750
I chose this
question on purpose,

00:46:05.750 --> 00:46:07.970
because I knew people would
score around this level--

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:10.240
so that about half of
the people get it right.

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:14.700
Then you find the largest
short-term learning gains.

00:46:14.700 --> 00:46:21.140
Now, I don't want you to lie
in bed tonight at 2 AM awake,

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:26.565
thinking, why is this
hole getting larger?

00:46:26.565 --> 00:46:28.690
Can I take another minute
of my precious time here?

00:46:28.690 --> 00:46:29.320
KARA MILLER: Yeah, go ahead.

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:29.945
ERIC MAZUR: OK.

00:46:29.945 --> 00:46:31.910
Take a jar of jam that's
in the refrigerator.

00:46:31.910 --> 00:46:33.597
Glass jar, metal lid.

00:46:33.597 --> 00:46:34.930
Take it out of the refrigerator.

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:35.880
You can't open it.

00:46:35.880 --> 00:46:38.090
What do you do?

00:46:38.090 --> 00:46:40.100
You run the lid under hot water.

00:46:40.100 --> 00:46:43.970
The lid is a ring and a plate,
and the ring gets bigger,

00:46:43.970 --> 00:46:45.660
so the hole in the
ring gets bigger.

00:46:45.660 --> 00:46:46.950
You knew this already.

00:46:46.950 --> 00:46:50.030
You say, well, you asked about
a plate, not about a jar.

00:46:50.030 --> 00:46:51.820
OK.

00:46:51.820 --> 00:46:53.570
I'm going to steal
your little piece here.

00:46:53.570 --> 00:46:54.430
KARA MILLER: Yeah, that's fine.

00:46:54.430 --> 00:46:56.138
ERIC MAZUR: Imagine
that we have a plate.

00:46:56.138 --> 00:46:57.252
No hole.

00:46:57.252 --> 00:46:57.960
Here's the plate.

00:46:57.960 --> 00:46:58.920
No hole.

00:46:58.920 --> 00:47:01.200
We draw a circle
on it, so now we

00:47:01.200 --> 00:47:03.230
have a plate with
a circle on it.

00:47:03.230 --> 00:47:05.260
We put it in the oven.

00:47:05.260 --> 00:47:07.600
Turn up the temperature,
the plate expands.

00:47:07.600 --> 00:47:10.700
What happens to the
diameter of the hole?

00:47:10.700 --> 00:47:11.430
Gets larger.

00:47:11.430 --> 00:47:13.940
Everything gets larger, so
that has to get larger, too.

00:47:13.940 --> 00:47:15.390
You said, that's unfair.

00:47:15.390 --> 00:47:17.360
You asked about a metal
plate with a hole,

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:18.640
and if there's a
hole then the atoms

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:20.150
are going to expand
into the hole.

00:47:20.150 --> 00:47:22.590
In fact, most of
you had that answer.

00:47:22.590 --> 00:47:24.550
Let me show you what's
wrong with that.

00:47:24.550 --> 00:47:28.200
Imagine we go outside and we
form a circle holding hands.

00:47:28.200 --> 00:47:32.630
We are the atoms at
the edge of the hole.

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:36.030
Now we step in towards
the center of the whole.

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:39.580
What just happened to
the distance between us?

00:47:39.580 --> 00:47:41.310
It gets smaller.

00:47:41.310 --> 00:47:43.270
We get crunched together.

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:45.110
It can't do it, because
we need more space.

00:47:45.110 --> 00:47:45.910
We're shaking more.

00:47:45.910 --> 00:47:49.071
The only way to increase the
distance is to take a few of us

00:47:49.071 --> 00:47:49.570
away.

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:51.260
But atoms don't
disappear like that.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:54.810
Or, to make the whole larger.

00:47:54.810 --> 00:47:56.010
You won't forget this.

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:07.180
KARA MILLER: OK, so how do
you take that kind of response

00:48:07.180 --> 00:48:11.110
and that kind of
engagement and replicate it

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:12.370
across more college classes?

00:48:12.370 --> 00:48:14.420
Because I did not have
any college classes

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:16.934
where anybody brought
anything this into it.

00:48:16.934 --> 00:48:18.350
I had college
classes where people

00:48:18.350 --> 00:48:21.220
read chapters of their books.

00:48:21.220 --> 00:48:22.817
Like chapter eight
today, because this

00:48:22.817 --> 00:48:24.150
is the eighth week of the class.

00:48:24.150 --> 00:48:26.520
So how do you change things?

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:28.140
Is that possible to do?

00:48:28.140 --> 00:48:29.779
Are teachers too
resistant to that?

00:48:29.779 --> 00:48:31.320
ERIC MAZUR: Change
is very difficult,

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:33.420
for a large number of reasons.

00:48:33.420 --> 00:48:35.710
The first one is, most
teachers are perfectly

00:48:35.710 --> 00:48:38.140
happy with what they're doing.

00:48:38.140 --> 00:48:41.050
There's no indication that
there's anything wrong, really,

00:48:41.050 --> 00:48:43.577
and change is
threatening, because you

00:48:43.577 --> 00:48:45.910
don't know what it's going
to do to your end of semester

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:46.420
evaluation.

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:48.670
You don't know how it's
going to affect you.

00:48:48.670 --> 00:48:52.660
So unless there's a real
reason to change, why change?

00:48:52.660 --> 00:48:53.990
So that's one problem.

00:48:53.990 --> 00:48:58.350
The second thing is that the
students also demand lecturing.

00:48:58.350 --> 00:49:00.310
By the time to get into
college they've already

00:49:00.310 --> 00:49:05.360
been pre-conditioned
to think, the professor

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:06.530
should be lecturing me.

00:49:06.530 --> 00:49:09.160
In fact, I have
some students who--

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:11.370
after I switched to this
interactive teaching, which

00:49:11.370 --> 00:49:14.220
has been 24 years
ago now-- write

00:49:14.220 --> 00:49:17.380
at the end of their
evaluation questionnaire,

00:49:17.380 --> 00:49:20.530
Professor Mazur is not
teaching us anything.

00:49:20.530 --> 00:49:24.120
We have to learn
it all ourselves.

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:26.650
So I think there's resistance
from the students, too.

00:49:27.370 --> 00:49:30.110
And, of course, higher
education depends on K

00:49:30.110 --> 00:49:31.045
through 12 education.

00:49:31.045 --> 00:49:33.170
K through 12 education
depends on higher education.

00:49:33.170 --> 00:49:36.240
So it's all sort of an
interlocking mechanism that

00:49:36.240 --> 00:49:38.166
prevents change,
in a certain sense.

00:49:38.166 --> 00:49:40.790
KARA MILLER: I want to get your
